-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Dangote, Kapchorua Tea, Williamson Are Active
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-06-30T16:30:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-30/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-dangote-kapchorua-tea-williamson-are-active.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  gained for
a sixth day, rising 0.1 percent to 1,654.16. The measure rose
0.9 percent in the three months through June.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  retreated 0.3 percent to 74.40 at
the close in Nairobi. The East African nation’s index rose 7.5
percent in the second quarter, a third of gains. The  Nigerian
Stock Exchange’s All Share Index  increased 0.1 percent to
25,384.14, according to its website.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  dropped 2 percent to
719.50, while the  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated
0.7 percent to 6,548.59, a fourth day of declines.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Dangote Sugar Refinery Plc  (DANGSUGA NL), a Nigerian
processor of the sweetener, rallied the highest in almost three
months, advancing 10 kobo, or 0.5 percent, to 20.3 naira. The
company announced plans to pay a dividend of 1 naira per share
for the year through December 2009.  
 Kapchorua Tea Co.  (KPTC KN), a Kenyan producer of the
leaves, rose to the highest level in more than three months,
climbing 5 shillings, or 3.5 percent, to 150 shillings. The
industry regulator said first-half tea output in the East
African nation grew 15 percent from a year earlier.  George
Williamson Kenya Ltd.  (GWKL KN), which also grows tea, gained
for the first time this week, rising 5 shillings, or 2.5
percent, to 218 shillings.  
